# Example — what a user-level CLAUDE.md looks like

> **DO NOT** copy this to `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md` blindly — it would apply
> to all your Claude Code sessions on this machine. This file is for
> illustration of the user-level (Level 1) format described in Module 5
> Concept 5.1.

A user-level `CLAUDE.md` lives at `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md`, is **not** in any
project's version control, and contains things specific to *you*, regardless
of which project you're in.

## Example contents

```markdown
# Personal preferences

- I prefer terse, code-first responses. Lead with the change, then explain.
- When summarizing a diff, don't restate every line — only highlight risks.
- Use my preferred git workflow: rebase, never merge.
- Default to TypeScript whenever a language choice is open.
- I run on macOS — use macOS-appropriate shell commands.

# Editor preferences

- Use 2-space indent unless the project's CLAUDE.md or .editorconfig says otherwise.
- Prefer named exports over default exports.

# Working style

- Ask before making more than 10 file changes in a single response.
- Show me diffs in unified format.
```

## Hierarchy reminder

User-level rules (this file) are overlaid by project-level rules (a project's
`CLAUDE.md`), which are in turn overlaid by directory-level rules. More
specific scopes WIN on conflicts — a project's coding-style preference
overrides your personal one when you're working in that project.
